Thank you for tuning into our discussion! Please check out our jobs at: http://t.co/EFVdYLnMfj. #MyNextJob
A12: The more you know about the company and role, the more you stand out in the crowd. #MyNextJob
A12: Be engaging, available, responsive, transparent, qualified, thorough, diligent, decisive & likable #MyNextJob
A11: Or send a thank-you email to team through your recruiter to every person you interviewed with. #MyNextJob
A11: Send wine and gifts to each team member. Just kidding! Personalized thank you emails work perfectly for tech companies #MyNextJob
A10: Reach out to someone who you know that works there to get the inside scoop. #MyNextJob
A10: The careers section of the website tells a lot about a company so utilize it to your advantage in doing your research. #MyNextJob
A10: Research the interview panel on @LinkedIn to find commonalities. Ask about interests and team values during your interview. #MyNextJob
A9: Show your personality by incorporating something unique about yourself in some of your answers. #MyNextJob
A9: Give yourself plenty of time to get to your interview. Punctuality is important in making that great first impression! #MyNextJob
A9: Be confident, excited, presentable & prepared. Show them WHY you want to be part of their team! #MyNextJob - @AppDynamics is hiring!
A8: Ask about the culture of the company and why people are excited about being there. #MyNextJob
A8: Depending on the role, ask different questions. We like these @USNews suggestions: http://t.co/307BkhmEd4 #MyNextJob
A7: Avoid coming across rehearsed during the interview. We look for personality & cultural fit in addition to your skills. #MyNextJob
A7: Mock interviews are great! Practice going over your resume and what you'd like to highlight during the actual interview. #MyNextJob
A7: Research the three P's: Product, People, & (company) Progression. Also look at competitors, culture, media buzz, @glassdoor. #MyNextJob
A6: Highlight in your cover letter what speaks to you about the role and the company. #MyNextJob
A6: Better to be casual in your cover letter. We want to know you! #MyNextJob
A6: Avoid misspelling the company's name or the person you're addressing. This is usually a 'no' for us at @AppDynamics. #MyNextJob
A6: Non-technical positions are frequently expected to have cover letters. Make them concise/well written, no more than 1/2 pg #MyNextJob
A5: Keeping it tailored to the job is most important. #MyNextJob
A5 Functional, concise resumes are best -- highlight relevant experience by tailoring resume to job description (1-3 pages) #MyNextJob
A4: Combo of functional and chronological resumes, depending on role. Technical should be functional, sales/marketing chrono. #MyNextJob
.@kimberleykasper Agreed with spell check. This is quite important. #MyNextJob
A3: Avoid hard-to-read or overly stylized resumes. Very distracting to get to the meat of the experience. #MyNextJob
A3: Best resumes are up-to-date, proof-read, concise, relevant to the position, have keywords, & highlight successes. #MyNextJob
A2: Also, highlight groups/orgs that you belong to or follow. That will help you stand out. #MyNextJob
Avoid standing out in a negative way on social media outlets. Potential employers can see what you write! #MyNextJob
A2: Make your social media brand #professional. Follow & interact w/ companies, build positive brand, make your profile private #MyNextJob
Definitely having a clear and professional photo for your Linkedin profile helps.#MyNextJob
Make your #LinkedIn profile stand out by using accurate job titles, role & brief description of responsibilities for past 5 yrs #MyNextJob
